Occam states the distinction still more clearly. “ Fallaciae in dictione sunt illa penes quas secundum omnes modos peccant sophistica argumenta com- posita ex signis voluntarie institutis, Fallaciae extra dictionem sunt illae pene quas peccant argumenta tam composita ex signis voluntarie institutis quam composita ex signis naturali- ter significantibus.” Logica, iii. 4. cap. l. The former arise from defecta in the arbitrary signs of thought, and hence are generally confined toa single language, and disappear on being translated into another. The latter are in the thought itself‚ whether materially‚ in the false application of notione to things, or formally, in the violation of the laws by which the operatione of the reason should be govemed; and thus adhere to the thought, in whatever language it may be ex· pressed.
